CalciTrack Heart Health Glossary
Making Sense of Your Screening Results

1. The Big Picture
10-Year Risk Score: Think of this as a weather forecast for your heart. It tells us the percentage chance of a heart event (like a heart attack) happening in the next 10 years if we don't make changes today.

Triage: This is a traffic light system. Green means keep up the good work; Orange means we need to look closer and perhaps adjust your lifestyle; Red means we need to see a heart specialist right away.

2. Genetic and Inflammatory Markers
Lp(a) [Lipoprotein-alpha]: We call this "Sticky Cholesterol." Unlike the regular cholesterol you get from food, this one is mostly decided by your genes (your family history). If it is high, it makes it easier for blockages to form in your pipes (arteries).

hs-CRP: This is a measure of "Fire" (inflammation) in your body. If your arteries are irritated or "on fire," they are more likely to trap cholesterol and create a blockage. A high score means we need to "put out the fire" with medicine or diet.

3. Key Measurements
BMI (South Asian): This measures if your weight is healthy for your height. For South Asians, we have a "Hidden Risk"—we tend to carry more fat around our belly even if we look thin. That is why our "Warning Zone" starts earlier, at a score of 23.

Systolic Blood Pressure: This is the pressure in your pipes when your heart beats. If it is too high, it's like having too much water pressure in an old garden hose—eventually, it can cause a leak or a burst.

4. Special Factors for Women
Pregnancy History: Did you have high blood pressure (Preeclampsia) or high sugar (Gestational Diabetes) during pregnancy? Even if it went away after the baby was born, it acts as a "stress test" for your heart and tells us you might need more care later in life.

5. Specialized Testing
CAC Score (Calcium Score): This is like taking a photo of your heart's pipes to see if there is any "rust" (calcium/plaque) building up. It helps doctors decide exactly how much medicine you need.

For the Health Worker: "The Simple Swap"
When explaining results, try using these phrases:

Instead of "Atherosclerosis," say "Hardening of the pipes."

Instead of "Risk Stratification," say "Finding your heart's safety zone."

Instead of "Lipid Management," say "Cleaning the grease out of the system."
